s participation in the movement and her childhood as an immigrant in the South; the bestseller The Silence of Our Friends, by Mark Long, Jim Demonakos, and Nate Powell (2012), set in Houston's Third Ward in 1967; and Howard Cruse's Stuck Rubber Baby (1995), whose protagonist is a closeted gay man involved in the movement. In choosing these five works, Jorge Santos also explores how this medium allows readers to participate in collective memory making, and what the books reveal about the process by which history is (re)told, (re)produced, and (re)narrativized. Concluding the work is Santos’s interview with Ho Che Anderson.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCivil rights movements in art. 0aCivil rights movements in literature. 0aCivil rights movementszUnited StatesxHistoryxIn art. 0aComic books, strips, etcxHistory and criticism. 0aGraphic novelsxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Comics & Graphic Novels.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31826340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477318287423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477318287/original  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK